class "JObject" as JObject << (E,#f59e0b) >>
class "JArray" as JArray << (E,#f59e0b) >>
class "TextFile" as TextFile << (E,#f59e0b) >>
class "CanonicalFile" as CanonicalFile << (E,#f59e0b) >>
class "RaiPath" as RaiPath << (E,#f59e0b) >>
class "SearchExpression" as SearchExpression << (E,#f59e0b) >>
enum Compare << (E,#f59e0b) >> {
	JSON
	ByProperty
}

ItemsBase <|-- PitItems
JsonPitBase <|-- Pit
TextFile <|-- MasterFlagFile
MasterFlagFile <|-- ProcessFlagFile
CanonicalFile <|-- PitFile
JObject <|-- PitItem

JsonPitBase --> PitFile : owns
JsonPitBase --> ProcessFlagFile : uses
JsonPitBase --> MasterFlagFile : uses
PitItems --> PitItem : history
Pit --> PitItems : stores
Pit --> PitItem : adds / retrieves
Pit --> JArray : imports / exports
PitItemExtensions ..> PitItem : compares
PitItem ..> JArray : extends from
Item ..> SearchExpression : filters with

note right of Pit
	Recommended usage:
	keep one long-lived Pit instance
	in memory per feature/service,
	and use Save() as the explicit
	persistence and sync boundary.
end note

note bottom of JsonPitBase
	JsonPit's server-side model is best described as
	asynchronous persistence with eventual durability.
end note

@enduml
